subSubSection.paragraph:
There is significant variation in the apex of the parameres of the aedeagus. The paramere tip is weakly sclerotized, as evidenced by its very pale to white appearance in cleared specimens (e.g., Fig. 
5A-J
). This tip varies from nearly evenly rounded (e.g., Fig. 
5D, G
) to possessing some level of indentation on the inner margin (e.g., Fig. 
5A, H
). Although this variation seems in part to be real, it also seems to be partly caused by artificial distortions; for example, the weakly sclerotized apex may become indented or inflated depending on the state of the genitalia during preparation. This would explain why there is a large variation in form as well as why the tip appears to be exhibit subtly asymmetry between parameres (e.g., Fig. 
5C, F
).
